[[File:LocationBermuda.png|thumb|right|Bermuda in respect to the [[Southern United States]] and the [[Greater Antilles]].]]
{{Template: English language}}
'''Bermudian English''' is a [[Regional accents of English|regional accent of English]] found in [[Bermuda]], a British [[British Overseas Territories|overseas territory]] in the [[North Atlantic]]. [[Standard English]] is used in professional settings and in writing, while [[vernacular]] Bermudian English is spoken on more casual occasions.<ref>Ruth Thomas, "Notes on Bermudian Language", in "Bermuda connections", ''Smithsonian Folklife Festival. 2001''. Washington, DC: Smithsonian Institution, 2001.</ref>  The Bermudian accent began to develop following settlement in the early 17th century, and retains traits of [[Early Modern English|Elizabethan English]].<ref>Petrone, Kelly.  [http://www.bermudatourism.com/Press/skins/aqua/Cover_Letter.pdf Welcome to the Bermuda Department of Tourism's Media Information Kit] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101222084017/http://www.bermudatourism.com/Press/skins/aqua/Cover_Letter.pdf |date=December 22, 2010 }}, Corbin & Associates, Ltd</ref>

Casual observers tend to have difficulty in placing the Bermudian accent, as it differs from those that are clearly [[British English|British]], [[American English|American]] or [[Caribbean English|Caribbean]]; they also note that the accent tends to vary between individuals.<ref>Weller, Anthony. [https://www.nytimes.com/2003/06/15/magazine/celebration-bermuda.html Celebration Bermuda], ''The New York Times'', June 15, 2003</ref>  To Americans, it sounds slightly British, while the British find it more American.

==Categorisation==

Bermudian English has been called "one of the most severely underresearched varieties of English".<ref>Cecilia Cutler, Stephanie Hackert and Chanti Seymour, "Bermuda and Bahamas", in Ulrich Ammon (ed.), ''Sociolinguistics. An International Handbook''. 2nd ed. Vol. 3. Walter de Gruyter, 2006. {{ISBN|3-11-018418-4}}. p. 2066.</ref> It primarily shows a mixture of traits typical of British English and American English, and is generally classified as a form of American (rather than Caribbean) English.<ref>Tom McArthur (ed.), ''Oxford Companion to the English Language''. Oxford and New York: Oxford University Press, 1992. {{ISBN|0-19-214183-X}}. pp. 116, 352.</ref> The most detailed scholarly study of Bermudian English, in 1933, stated that this type of speech "would create least remark, if indeed any, between, say, [[Norfolk, Virginia]], and [[Charleston, South Carolina]]";<ref>Harry Morgan Ayres, "Bermudian English", ''American Speech'' 8:1 (1933), p. 4. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/3181810 Available online to JSTOR subscribers]</ref> British-Bermudian actor [[Earl Cameron (actor)|Earl Cameron]] noted that because the Bermudian accent sounded American, he was able to land a speaking role in 1942.<ref>{{cite book | last=Bourne|first=Stephen|title=Black in British frame|publisher=Continuum International Publishing Group|year=2005|isbn=978-0-8264-7898-6 |pages =106}}</ref> Large scale West Indian immigration to Bermuda, especially Sandys and Pembroke parishes, began with the expansion of the [[Royal Naval Dockyard, Bermuda|Royal Naval Dockyard]] (as a result of the lack of cheap, unskilled labour in Bermuda) at the turn of the twentieth century, and affected the dialect of certain demographic groups. Consequently, in certain aspects of vocalization, some Bermudian English dialects are close to some versions of Caribbean English,<ref>Cecilia Cutler, "English in the Turks and Caicos Islands: A look at Grand Turk" in ''Contact Englishes of the Eastern Caribbean'', ed. Michael Aceto and Jeffrey P. Williams. John Benjamins: 2003, pp. 51–80. {{ISBN|90-272-4890-7}}. p. 60.</ref> and some would bracket all these varieties to the broad region of the "English-speaking West Indies".<ref>John Wells, ''Accents of English 3: Beyond the British Isles''. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1982. {{ISBN|0-521-29719-2}}. p. 561.</ref> Azorean Portuguese has also impacted on Bermudian English as a result of immigration since the 1840s.

==Characteristics==

The accent's most evident characteristic is a variation in letter/sound assignment. The switching of {{IPA|[v]}} and {{IPA|[w]}},<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9hM6lBsiHswC&dq=bermudian+english+spelling&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%22The+Bermudian+inflection+is+characterized%22 ''Dependents information on Bermuda''], United States. Dept. of the Air Force, 1956, page 3</ref> characteristic of many dialects in Southern England during the 18th and 19th centuries,<ref>[http://www.humnet.unipi.it/slifo/articolosantipolo.pdf On the Opposite Sides of the Continuum: Standard British English and Cockney. A Historical Outline of the Parallel Developments of the Two Varieties], Matteo Santipolo, Università degli Studi di Padova, Department of Linguistic and Literary Studies</ref> and of {{IPA|[d]}} and {{IPA|[dʒ]}} (similarly to the dialects of English speakers of Gaelic heritage), when combined with a [[front vowel]], can both be seen in the title of a humorous glossary, ''Bermewjan Vurds'' (Bermudian Words).<ref>Peter A. Smith and Fred M. Barritt, ''[https://pdos.csail.mit.edu/archive/decouto/bvurds.html Bermewjan Vurds - a Dictionary of Conversational Bermudian]''. Hamilton, Bermuda: Lizard Press, 1988.</ref>  The use of {{IPA|[æ]}} and {{IPA|[ɛ]}} is interchangeable and vowels are often elongated.

